


When a user wants to access the website, they type www.foobar.com in their browser.

The browser sends a DNS request to resolve www.foobar.com into an IP address. The domain name foobar.com has a www record that points to the server IP address 8.8.8.8.

After DNS resolution, the browser sends an HTTP or HTTPS request to the server over the Internet using TCP/IP.

A server is a physical or virtual machine that provides services to users over a network. In this infrastructure, one server contains all the components needed to run the website.

Nginx is the web server. Its role is to receive the user request, serve static files, and forward dynamic requests to the application server.

The application server runs the backend logic of the website. It uses the application files, which are the code base of the website.

The MySQL database stores and retrieves the website data, such as users, content, and application information.

The server communicates with the user's computer using TCP/IP, and the website traffic uses HTTP or HTTPS.

The www record in www.foobar.com is commonly a CNAME record. However, in this required design, www.foobar.com points to the server IP address 8.8.8.8.

This infrastructure has several issues. First, it has a Single Point of Failure because everything is hosted on one server. If the server goes down, the whole website becomes unavailable.

Second, maintenance can cause downtime. If the web server needs to be restarted or new code is deployed, the website may be unavailable during that time.

Third, this infrastructure cannot scale well. All incoming traffic goes to one server, so if too many users access the website, the server may become slow or crash.
